<ul><li>Mustard seed oil is considered unfit for human consumption in many =
parts of the world and is therefore not readily available. A poor alternati=
ve can be made by crackling 1 <a href=3D"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Cook=
book:Teaspoon" title=3D"Cookbook:Teaspoon">tsp</a> of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikibooks.org/wiki/Cookbook:Mustard" title=3D"Cookbook:Mustard">mustard</a=
> seeds in approximately 2 <a href=3D"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Cookboo=
k:Tablespoon" title=3D"Cookbook:Tablespoon">tbs</a> of very hot <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Cookbook:Vegetable_Oil" title=3D"Cookbook:Veg=
etable Oil">vegetable</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Cookb=
ook:Olive_Oil" title=3D"Cookbook:Olive Oil">olive oil</a>. Allow to cool th=
en use in place of mustard seed oil.</li>
<li>It is possible to make a tikka with almost any meat, the most commonly =
used other than chicken being <a href=3D"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Cook=
book:Lamb" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cookbook:Lamb">lamb</a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Cookbook:Mutton" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Cookbook:Mutton">mutton</a>.</li>
<li>Tikka can be served either as main meal or as an appetiser.</li>
<li>Powdered or dried ingredients can be substituted for fresh, but at the =
expense of taste.</li>
<li>Some people prefer to make tikka with meat on-the-bone for improved fla=
vour.</li></ul>
